  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adenomas: Resect to prevent bleed or cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question assesses knowledge of benign liver lesions, specifically hepatic adenomas. Option A correctly identifies adenomas as true neoplasms with significant complication risks, necessitating resection in most cases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatic adenomas are true neoplasms, unlike focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) or hemangiomas. They are characterized by a lack of portal tracts and bile ducts, and can be associated with oral contraceptive use. Their primary risks include spontaneous hemorrhage (which can be life-threatening) and malignant transformation into hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), particularly in larger lesions (>5cm) or specific subtypes (e.g., beta-catenin activated). Due to these serious complications, surgical resection is generally recommended for symptomatic adenomas, those larger than 5 cm, or those with high-risk features.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The option 'Focal n' is incomplete and cannot be evaluated. However, if it referred to Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH), FNH is generally a benign, non-neoplastic lesion that rarely requires intervention unless symptomatic or diagnostic uncertainty exists.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatic Adenoma | Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH) | Hepatic Hemangioma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Nature** | True neoplasm | Hyperplastic response | Vascular malformation |\n| **Malignant Potential** | Yes (especially >5cm, certain subtypes) | No | No |\n| **Risk of Hemorrhage** | Significant | Rare | Rare (unless very large) |\n| **Association** | Oral contraceptives, anabolic steroids | None specific | None specific |\n| **Management** | Resection (symptomatic, >5cm, high-risk) | Observation (most), resection (symptomatic/uncertain) | Observation (most) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adenomas are true neoplasms with malignant potential; FNH is not.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), adenomas often appear as well-circumscribed, heterogeneous masses, sometimes with areas of hemorrhage or fat. They typically enhance arterial phase and wash out in portal venous phase, but less rapidly than HCC. Intraoperatively, they are usually encapsulated and can be pale or yellowish, often with visible vessels on the surface.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) Guidelines for the Management of Benign Liver Lesions (2017) recommend resection for hepatic adenomas >5cm or those with high-risk features due to hemorrhage and malignant transformation risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adenomas are true neoplasms with a predisposition for complications and sho | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Focal n | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
