  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let hemobilia bleed your knowledge dry; embolize the problem!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because hemobilia resulting from percutaneous cholangiography is typically minor and self-limiting, often resolving without aggressive intervention. This distinguishes it from other, more severe forms of hemobilia that require urgent management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemobilia, or bleeding into the biliary tree, presents with the classic triad of abdominal pain, jaundice, and gastrointestinal bleeding. While trauma is the most common cause, iatrogenic injuries, such as those from percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography (PTC), can also lead to this condition. The severity of hemobilia dictates management; minor cases, particularly post-procedural, often resolve spontaneously due to the tamponade effect of blood clots within the bile ducts or the small caliber of the injured vessel. Severe hemobilia, however, necessitates prompt diagnosis via arteriography and definitive treatment, most commonly through transarterial embolization to occlude the bleeding vessel, thereby preserving the liver parenchyma and avoiding more invasive surgical approaches.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Trauma, not tumors, is by far the most common cause of hemobilia. Tumors are relatively uncommon etiologies.\nOption B (Incorrect): The primary treatment for severe hemobilia is arteriographic embolization, not an operation. Surgery is reserved for cases refractory to embolization or when recognized intraoperatively.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ultrasonography is a very nonspecific diagnostic technique for hemobilia. Arteriography remains the best diagnostic method for localizing the bleeding site.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Most Common Cause | Primary Treatment (Severe) | Diagnostic Modality |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Hemobilia** | Trauma | Arteriographic Embolization | Arteriography |\n| **Post-PC Hemobilia** | Iatrogenic (procedure) | Observation (usually minor) | Clinical, imaging |\n| **Tumor-related** | Less common | Embolization/Surgery | Arteriography, CT/MRI |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Trauma is the leading cause of hemobilia; embolization is first-line for severe cases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nArteriography is the gold standard for diagnosing hemobilia, often revealing the site of bleeding, such as a pseudoaneurysm or arteriovenous fistula. Intraoperatively, blood clots may be found within the biliary tree, and direct ligation or repair of the bleeding vessel may be necessary if embolization fails.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no single overarching guideline specifically addresses hemobilia, principles from the American Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) for liver injury management and general interventional radiology guidelines for embolization are relevant.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tumors are the most common cause. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The primary treatment of severe hemobilia is an operation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Percutaneous cholangiographic hemobilia is usually minor. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Ultrasonography usually reveals a specific diagnosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) By far the most common cause of hemobilia is trauma. Tumors also may cause the syndrome but are rela** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
