  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HVWP: Your compass to portal hypertension's cause.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is AC because both Portal vein thrombosis and Schistosomiasis are causes of presinusoidal portal hypertension. In these conditions, the obstruction occurs before the hepatic sinusoids, leading to an elevated portal venous pressure but a normal hepatic venous wedge pressure (HVWP).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatic venous wedge pressure (HVWP) is a critical diagnostic tool for localizing the site of obstruction in portal hypertension. When a catheter is wedged into a hepatic vein, it measures the pressure distal to the obstruction. If the obstruction is at the sinusoidal or post-sinusoidal level (e.g., cirrhosis, alcoholic hepatitis), the HVWP will be elevated, reflecting the high portal pressure. However, if the obstruction is presinusoidal (e.g., portal vein thrombosis, schistosomiasis), the HVWP remains normal because the pressure in the hepatic sinusoids and veins distal to the obstruction is not elevated. This differential pressure reading precisely identifies the anatomical location of increased resistance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Alcoholic cirrhosis) (Incorrect): Alcoholic cirrhosis causes sinusoidal portal hypertension, meaning the obstruction is within the hepatic sinusoids. In this scenario, both portal venous pressure and hepatic venous wedge pressure would be elevated.\nOption D (Alcoholic hepatitis) (Incorrect): Similar to cirrhosis, alcoholic hepatitis causes sinusoidal or post-sinusoidal obstruction. Therefore, it would also present with elevated portal venous pressure and an elevated hepatic venous wedge pressure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Portal Hypertension | Site of Obstruction | HVWP | Examples |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Presinusoidal | Before sinusoids | Normal | Portal vein thrombosis, Schistosomiasis |\n| Sinusoidal | Within sinusoids | Elevated | Cirrhosis (alcoholic, viral), Alcoholic hepatitis |\n| Postsinusoidal | After sinusoids | Elevated | Budd-Chiari syndrome, Veno-occlusive disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal HVWP + high portal pressure = presinusoidal block.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question includes a generic image tag `![Image](/images/review_bank/37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery_7.jpeg)`. For portal vein thrombosis, Doppler ultrasound or CT angiography would typically show a thrombus within the portal vein. In schistosomiasis, ultrasound or CT imaging might reveal periportal fibrosis (Symmers' fibrosis) and significant splenomegaly.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance on the Management of Portal Vein Thrombosis in Patients With Cirrhosis: 2020 recommends diagnostic imaging to confirm portal vein thrombosis and guides management strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein thrombosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Alcoholic cirrhosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Schistosomiasis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Alcoholic hepatitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: AC) Pressure measured by wedging a catheter into a hepatic vein (hepatic venous wedge pressure) closely ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
