  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Decompress the gallbladder, de-stress the surgeon.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that early antibiotic therapy and intraoperative gallbladder decompression are crucial aspects of managing acute calculous cholecystitis. These interventions directly address infection control and surgical safety, respectively, optimizing patient outcomes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAntibiotic therapy initiated as soon as the diagnosis is made is paramount in acute calculous cholecystitis to combat bacterial proliferation and prevent septic complications, significantly improving postoperative recovery. Intraoperatively, a tensely distended gallbladder can obscure critical anatomy and increase the risk of iatrogenic injury. Decompression with a trocar provides immediate relief, allowing for safer and more precise dissection of the cystic duct and artery, thereby reducing operative time and potential complications. This strategic maneuver transforms a challenging field into a more manageable one, upholding the principles of surgical safety and efficacy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Immediate operation is not indicated for *all* patients; those with significant comorbidities may require an initial period of observation and supportive care before surgery.\nOption D (Incorrect): While useful, an operative cholangiogram is not routinely performed in *every* patient with acute cholecystitis, especially if the biliary ducts are friable or the procedure is deemed unsafe.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Cholecystitis | Elective Cholecystectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Timing of Surgery** | Early (within 24-72h) for healthy; delayed for high-risk after stabilization | Scheduled, non-urgent |\n| **Antibiotics** | Initiated pre-op, continued 24h post-op (longer if peritonitis) | Often not required, or single pre-op dose |\n| **Gallbladder Decompression** | Often beneficial due to distension | Less frequently needed |\n| **Operative Cholangiogram** | Selective, if safe; ducts may be friable | Routinely considered to delineate anatomy and detect stones |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute cholecystitis management balances early intervention with patient-specific risk assessment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, acute cholecystitis often presents with a distended, inflamed gallbladder, sometimes with pericholecystic fluid. Decompression would show a gush of bile, immediately reducing the tension and making the cystic duct and artery more accessible for safe dissection. The surrounding tissues may appear edematous and friable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend early cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) for Grade I and II acute cholecystitis, and initial conservative management for Grade III or high-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Operation should be performed in all patients as soon as the diagnosis is m | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Antibiotic therapy should be initiated as soon as the diagnosis is made. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dissection of the gallbladder is facilitated by decompression of the organ  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | An operative cholangiogram should be done in every patient. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BC) DISCUSSION: Cholecystectomy should be done in an otherwise healthy patient as soon as the diagnosis ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
