  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GIP: Giving insulin a gut feeling for glucose.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Gastric inhibitory peptide (GIP). Orally administered glucose elicits a greater insulin response than intravenous glucose due to the enteroinsular axis, where gut hormones like GIP potentiate insulin secretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe enteroinsular axis describes the phenomenon where ingested nutrients stimulate the release of gut hormones that enhance pancreatic beta-cell insulin secretion. GIP, also known as glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide, is a key incretin hormone released from K-cells in the duodenum and jejunum in response to glucose and fat. It significantly potentiates glucose-stimulated insulin release, ensuring a more robust and timely insulin response to a meal compared to direct glucose infusion. Other gut peptides like GLP-1 also contribute to this effect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Somatostatin is an inhibitory hormone that suppresses the release of many other hormones, including insulin, glucagon, and growth hormone.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pancreatic polypeptide is released from pancreatic F cells and plays roles in satiety, gallbladder contraction, and pancreatic exocrine secretion, but it does not primarily potentiate insulin secretion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Secretin is released from S cells in the duodenum in response to acid and stimulates bicarbonate and water secretion from the pancreas and bile ducts, but it is not a primary incretin hormone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Primary Source | Key Action related to Glucose/Insulin |\n|---|---|---|\n| GIP (Gastric Inhibitory Peptide) | Duodenal/Jejunal K-cells | Potentiates glucose-stimulated insulin secretion (incretin effect) |\n| GLP-1 (Glucagon-like Peptide-1) | Ileal/Colonic L-cells | Potentiates glucose-stimulated insulin secretion, suppresses glucagon, slows gastric emptying |\n| Somatostatin | Pancreatic D-cells, GI tract | Inhibits insulin, glucagon, and other GI hormone secretion |\n| Secretin | Duodenal S-cells | Stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate and water secretion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the enteroinsular axis: oral glucose > IV glucose due to GIP and GLP-1.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not involve imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A. This is a basic science/physiology question, not directly covered by surgical guidelines.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastric inhibitory peptide | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Somatostatin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pancreatic polypeptide | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Secretin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a) Orally administered glucose stimulates a greater insulin response than an equivalent amount of intra** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
