  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let gallstones cause a repeat performance!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presented with mild gallstone pancreatitis that rapidly resolved. The correct management involves early cholecystectomy to prevent recurrence, often before hospital discharge, as the risk of another attack is high.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone pancreatitis occurs when gallstones obstruct the pancreaticobiliary ductal system. Even after resolution of the initial attack, the risk of recurrent pancreatitis is substantial (34-56% within 6 weeks) if the gallbladder remains in situ. Therefore, definitive management with cholecystectomy is crucial. Performing it before discharge prevents readmission for recurrent attacks, which can be more severe. Intraoperative cholangiography (IOC) is important to identify or rule out concomitant common bile duct stones, which might require further intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Elective cholecystectomy at approximately 8 weeks. This delay is too long. The high risk of recurrent pancreatitis within weeks necessitates earlier intervention to prevent another attack and potential complications.\nOption C (Incorrect): Endoscopic sphincterotomy before discharge followed by cholecystectomy at approximately 8 weeks. ERCP with sphincterotomy is generally reserved for patients with persistent biliary obstruction (e.g., cholangitis, jaundice, persistent CBD stone on imaging) or severe pancreatitis. For mild, resolved pancreatitis, it's not the first step, and delaying cholecystectomy is still problematic.\nOption D (Incorrect): Observation. Observation is inappropriate as it leaves the underlying cause (gallstones) untreated, leading to a very high risk of recurrent pancreatitis, which can be severe and life-threatening.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mild Gallstone Pancreatitis (Resolved) | Severe Gallstone Pancreatitis | Persistent CBD Obstruction/Cholangitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Timing of Cholecystectomy** | Before hospital discharge | After resolution of inflammation/stabilization | After ERCP/CBD clearance |\n| **Role of ERCP** | Not routinely indicated | Consider if persistent obstruction/cholangitis | Indicated (urgent) |\n| **Recurrence Risk (without cholecystectomy)** | High (34-56% within 6 weeks) | High | High |\n| **Goal** | Prevent recurrence | Manage complications, prevent recurrence | Relieve obstruction, prevent recurrence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mild gallstone pancreatitis? Cholecystectomy before discharge prevents recurrence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound would show cholelithiasis. Intraoperative cholangiography (IOC) would delineate the biliary tree, confirming patency or identifying common bile duct stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). Recommends cholecystectomy during the same admission for patients with gallstone pancreatitis who are clinically improving.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholecystectomy and intraoperative cholangiography before hospital discharg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Elective cholecystectomy at approximately 8 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Endoscopic sphincterotomy before discharge followed by cholecystectomy at a | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a) A patient who has simple cholelithiasis and an episode of acute pancreatitis is usually treated nono** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
