  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Jaundice saves lives, even in pancreatic cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key epidemiological and clinical characteristics of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma. Options A and C are correct because they accurately describe the typical distribution of tumors within the pancreas and the size differences observed at diagnosis based on location.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anatomical location of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma significantly impacts its clinical presentation and size at diagnosis. Tumors in the head of the pancreas often cause obstructive jaundice early due to their proximity to the common bile duct, leading to earlier detection when they are smaller (average 4-5 cm). Conversely, tumors in the body and tail are often asymptomatic until they are much larger (average 7-8 cm) and have potentially metastasized, as they do not typically impinge on the bile duct or duodenum until advanced stages. This difference in presentation drives the observed size disparity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The statement that 50% of pancreatic adenocarcinomas involve the gland diffusely at diagnosis is incorrect. The provided data indicates that only 5% to 15% are diffuse, not 50%.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pancreatic adenocarcinomas do not occur with equal frequency across the gland. There is a clear predilection for the head of the gland (60-70%), making this statement false.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Head of Pancreas | Body of Pancreas | Tail of Pancreas | Diffuse |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Frequency** | 60-70% | ~15% | ~10% | 5-15% |\n| **Typical Size at Dx** | 4-5 cm | 7-8 cm | 7-8 cm | Variable |\n| **Early Symptom** | Obstructive jaundice | Vague abdominal pain, weight loss | Vague abdominal pain, weight loss | Variable |\n| **Prognosis** | Often earlier diagnosis, but still poor | Often advanced at diagnosis | Often advanced at diagnosis | Very poor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pancreatic head tumors present early with jaundice; body/tail tumors are larger at diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (e.g., CT or MRI), a pancreatic head mass would often be associated with dilated intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts, and potentially a dilated pancreatic duct (double duct sign). Body and tail lesions, however, would typically present as larger, ill-defined masses with less prominent biliary dilation, often with evidence of vascular involvement or metastatic disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment, emphasizing the importance of early detection and multidisciplinary management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | For ductal adenocarcinoma, 60–70% of tumors arise in the head of the gland, | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fifty percent of pancreatic adenocarcinomas involve the gland diffusely at  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | For ductal adenocarcinomas, tumors of the body and tail are usually larger  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pancreatic adenocarcinomas occur with equal frequency within the head, body | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c) Sixty to 70% of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinomas occur in the head of the gland. About 15% reside i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
