  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer unresectability is often clear on CT: think distant spread or extensive local invasion.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies ascites and infiltration of the transverse colonic mesentery as indicators of unresectability for pancreatic head masses. These findings signify distant spread or extensive local invasion, making surgical cure unlikely.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT imaging is crucial for preoperative staging of pancreatic cancer, particularly in assessing resectability. While CT can sometimes overestimate resectability, it is highly accurate in identifying unresectable disease. Key CT findings indicating unresectability include distant metastases (e.g., ascites, liver metastases, peritoneal carcinomatosis), extensive local invasion (e.g., infiltration of adjacent organs like the colon or its mesentery, stomach, or major vessels beyond what can be safely resected), and arterial invasion. These signs suggest that complete tumor removal with negative margins is not achievable, precluding curative surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Common bile duct diameter of 2 cm) (Incorrect): While a dilated common bile duct indicates biliary obstruction, a common presentation of pancreatic head masses, it does not directly signify unresectability. The obstruction itself can be managed, and the tumor may still be localized.\nOption D (Dilatation of the main pancreatic duct to 1.5 cm) (Incorrect): Similar to CBD dilatation, a dilated pancreatic duct (often part of a 'double duct sign') is a common finding in pancreatic head masses causing obstruction. It indicates the presence of a mass but is not, by itself, a criterion for unresectability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Resectable | Unresectable |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Vascular Invasion** | No arterial abutment; Venous abutment < 180 degrees | Arterial abutment/invasion > 180 degrees; Venous occlusion/invasion |\n| **Distant Disease** | None | Ascites, Liver metastases, Peritoneal carcinomatosis |\n| **Local Invasion** | Confined to pancreas or minimal adjacent tissue | Invasion of adjacent organs (e.g., colon, stomach, major vessels) |\n| **Lymph Nodes** | Regional, within resection boundaries | Distant, outside resection boundaries |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ascites or distant organ invasion on CT means unresectable pancreatic cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, ascites appears as fluid accumulation in the peritoneal cavity, often seen in dependent areas. Infiltration of the transverse colonic mesentery would be visualized as stranding, thickening, or a mass effect extending from the pancreatic head tumor into the mesentery, potentially encasing vessels or invading the colon itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (e.g., 2023). Recommends multiphase CT for staging and assessing resectability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Common bile duct diameter of 2 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ascites | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Infiltration of the transverse colonic mesentery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Dilatation of the main pancreatic duct to 1.5 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, c) CT scans provide the best available radiologic information to determine whether or not a pancreatic ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
