  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Secretin test: Gastrin up, ZES is the scoop!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. This patient presents with classic signs of Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome (ZES), including multiple duodenal ulcers and elevated serum gastrin. The secretin stimulation test is the most definitive diagnostic tool to confirm gastrinoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrinomas are neuroendocrine tumors that autonomously secrete gastrin. Unlike normal G cells, which are inhibited by secretin, gastrinoma cells paradoxically respond to secretin by releasing a surge of gastrin. A rise in serum gastrin of >200 pg/mL (or >120 pg/mL depending on the specific criteria used) above baseline after intravenous secretin administration is highly diagnostic for gastrinoma, making an increase of 320 pg/mL a strong indicator.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Gastric acid analysis demonstrating fasting acid secretion of 3 mEq/h is within the normal range (typically 1-5 mEq/h). Gastrinoma is characterized by marked gastric acid hypersecretion, often with a basal acid output (BAO) >15 mEq/h or a BAO/MAO ratio >0.6.\nOption C (Incorrect): Enlarged gastric rugae on upper gastrointestinal contrast study can be seen in gastrinoma due to chronic hypergastrinemia and acid hypersecretion, leading to mucosal hypertrophy. However, this finding is non-specific and can also be present in other conditions like Ménétrier's disease, lymphoma, or chronic gastritis, making it less diagnostic than a secretin stimulation test.\nOption D (Incorrect): While an increase of 150 pg/mL in serum gastrin upon intravenous infusion of secretin would be suggestive, an increase of 320 pg/mL (as in Option A) is a more robust and commonly accepted positive threshold for the secretin stimulation test, making Option A a stronger diagnostic criterion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastrinoma | G-cell Hyperplasia | Normal | \n|---|---|---|---| \n| Basal Gastrin | Markedly Elevated (>100-1000 pg/mL) | Moderately Elevated (100-500 pg/mL) | <100 pg/mL | \n| Secretin Test | Gastrin increases (>200 pg/mL rise) | Gastrin decreases or no change | Gastrin decreases or no change | \n| BAO | Markedly Elevated (>15 mEq/h) | Moderately Elevated | 1-5 mEq/h | \n| Location | Duodenum (most common), Pancreas | Antrum | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Secretin paradoxically increases gastrin in gastrinoma, confirming the diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy revealed multiple duodenal ulcers, a common finding in ZES. For localization of gastrinomas, imaging modalities like CT, MRI, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and somatostatin receptor scintigraphy (SRS, e.g., Octreoscan) are used.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe North American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Neuroendocrine Tumors (2017) recommend the secretin stimulation test for diagnosis of gastrinoma when basal gastrin levels are equivocal.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | An increase of 320 pg/mL in serum gastrin upon intravenous infusion of secr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastric acid analysis demonstrating fasting acid secretion of 3 mEq/h | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Enlarged gastric rugae on upper gastrointestinal contrast study | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | An increase of 150 pg/mL in serum gastrin upon intravenous infusion of | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
