  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small insulinoma? Enucleate it, don't complicate it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Surgical enucleation of the tumor. This patient presents with classic symptoms and biochemical evidence of an insulinoma, confirmed by EUS showing a 1.2 cm mass in the pancreatic head. Given its small size and likely benign nature, enucleation is the appropriate curative surgical approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulinomas are typically solitary, benign adenomas, with 90% being amenable to surgical cure. The treatment of choice is surgical resection. Small, benign insulinomas, especially those not in close proximity to the main pancreatic duct, can often be managed with enucleation, regardless of their location within the pancreas. This preserves pancreatic parenchyma and minimizes surgical morbidity while achieving a cure. The insulin/glucose ratio of 0.5 and symptom reversal with glucose are classic for insulinoma, and the EUS finding confirms a localized lesion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Total pancreatectomy) (Incorrect): This is an overly aggressive procedure for a small, benign, localized insulinoma and would lead to significant endocrine and exocrine insufficiency.\nOption C (Long-term octreotide administration) (Incorrect): Octreotide is primarily used for symptomatic control in patients with unresectable, metastatic, or recurrent insulinomas, or as a bridge to surgery, not as primary definitive treatment for a resectable tumor.\nOption D (Primary radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is not a primary treatment modality for insulinomas, which are typically managed surgically. It may be considered in rare cases of unresectable or metastatic disease, but not as initial therapy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Enucleation | Distal Pancreatectomy | Pancreaticoduodenectomy | Medical Management (Octreotide) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Small, benign insulinoma, not near main pancreatic duct | Larger insulinomas (>2cm) or near duct in body/tail | Large/deep insulinomas in head/uncinate process, or near duct | Unresectable, metastatic, or recurrent disease; symptom control |\n| **Location** | Any part of pancreas | Body and tail | Head and uncinate process | N/A |\n| **Goal** | Curative, parenchyma-sparing | Curative | Curative | Symptom control, palliative |\n| **Morbidity** | Lower | Moderate | Higher | Minimal (drug-related) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Resectable insulinomas = surgical cure, often by enucleation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopic ultrasonography (EUS) is highly sensitive for localizing insulinomas, especially small ones, as demonstrated by the 1.2 cm mass in the pancreatic head. Intraoperatively, these tumors often appear as well-demarcated, firm nodules that can be palpated and enucleated from the surrounding pancreatic tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors (2023): Recommend surgical resection as the primary treatment for localized, resectable pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors, including insulinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical enucleation of the tumor | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Total pancreatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Long-term octreotide administration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Primary radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The treatment of insulinoma is surgical in nearly all cases. Insulinomas are found evenly distribute** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
