  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When glucose drops, C-peptide pops, unless it's a shot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with symptoms consistent with Whipple's triad (neurological symptoms with hypoglycemia), strongly suggesting an insulinoma. The next crucial step is to confirm endogenous hyperinsulinism and differentiate it from other causes of hypoglycemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulinoma is a rare neuroendocrine tumor that secretes insulin inappropriately, leading to hypoglycemia. The most reliable diagnostic approach involves a monitored fast, during which blood samples are taken for glucose and insulin levels. An elevated insulin-to-glucose (I:G) ratio (>0.4) in the presence of hypoglycemia is highly indicative of insulinoma. Furthermore, C-peptide is a byproduct of endogenous insulin synthesis. Elevated C-peptide levels confirm that the insulin is being produced by the body (endogenous), effectively ruling out surreptitious administration of exogenous insulin, which would result in low or undetectable C-peptide.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): An oral glucose tolerance test is contraindicated in suspected insulinoma as it can provoke severe hypoglycemia and is not diagnostic for this condition. The preferred diagnostic method is a monitored fast.\nOption D (Incorrect): Determination of serum prolactin levels is irrelevant to the diagnosis of hypoglycemia or insulinoma. Prolactin is a hormone primarily associated with pituitary function and lactation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Test | Purpose | Expected in Insulinoma | Differentiates from Exogenous Insulin |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Monitored Fast (Insulin/Glucose Ratio) | Confirm inappropriate insulin secretion during hypoglycemia | High I:G ratio (>0.4) | Yes (insulin high, glucose low) |\n| Serum C-peptide | Confirm endogenous insulin production | Elevated | Yes (elevated in insulinoma, low/normal with exogenous insulin) |\n| Serum Proinsulin | Confirm endogenous insulin production | Elevated | Yes (elevated in insulinoma, low/normal with exogenous insulin) |\n| Oral Glucose Tolerance Test | Not indicated for insulinoma | N/A (can be dangerous) | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Whipple's triad + hypoglycemia = think insulinoma; confirm with monitored fast, I:G ratio, and C-peptide.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative localization of insulinomas often involves endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), CT, or MRI, though these tumors can be small and difficult to find. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the pancreas and intraoperative ultrasound (IOUS) are critical for identifying these typically small, solitary lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Adult Hypoglycemic Disorders (2009) recommends a 72-hour supervised fast as the gold standard for diagnosing insulinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Oral glucose tolerance test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Determination of fasting insulin/glucose ratios | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Assay of serum C-peptide levels | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Determination of serum prolactin levels | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) A common mistake made in the evaluation of a patient with suspected insulinoma is to commence the ev** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
