  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gastrinoma: Duodenum and pancreatic head, the usual suspects.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A and D, indicating that gastrinomas are most commonly found in the pancreas to the right of the superior mesenteric vein (pancreatic head) and in the duodenum. This distribution defines the classic 'gastrinoma triangle,' a critical anatomical region for surgical exploration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrinomas, the tumors responsible for Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome, are neuroendocrine tumors that secrete gastrin. While they can occur in various locations, the vast majority (approximately 80-90%) are found within the 'gastrinoma triangle' (Passaro triangle). This triangle is bounded by the porta hepatis superiorly, the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum inferiorly, and the neck of the pancreas medially. This region encompasses the pancreatic head and the duodenum, making these the most common sites for tumor development and thus the primary targets for surgical localization and resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While gastrinomas can arise in the pancreas, the body and tail are significantly less common locations compared to the head of the pancreas.\nOption C (Incorrect): The gastric antrum contains G cells that produce gastrin, but it is not a common primary site for gastrinoma development. Gastrinomas are typically found in the duodenum or pancreas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastrinoma | Insulinoma | VIPoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Location** | Duodenum, Pancreatic Head | Pancreas (diffuse) | Pancreas (body/tail) |\n| **Hormone Secreted** | Gastrin | Insulin | Vasoactive Intestinal Peptide (VIP) |\n| **Syndrome** | Zollinger-Ellison | Hypoglycemia | Verner-Morrison (WDHA) |\n| **Associated MEN1** | ~25% | ~10% | Rare |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastrinomas love the duodenum and pancreatic head – think 'gastrinoma triangle'.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, careful palpation of the duodenum and pancreatic head is crucial. Intraoperative ultrasonography is highly effective for localizing small tumors, especially within the pancreas. Transillumination of the duodenal wall via upper endoscopy can also help identify small duodenal gastrinomas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines 2017: Recommend surgical resection for localized gastrinomas, emphasizing thorough exploration of the gastrinoma triangle.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pancreas to the right of the superior mesenteric vein | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pancreatic body and tail | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gastric antrum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Duodenum | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D) The majority of gastrinomas have been identified to the right of the superior mesenteric vessels wit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
