  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 VIPoma: Diarrhea so bad, you'll be VIP-ing to the ER!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because neoplastic hypersecretion of vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) characteristically leads to severe watery diarrhea, which causes significant potassium loss (hypokalemia) and often results in hypochlorhydria due to VIP's inhibitory effect on gastric acid secretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) is a potent gastrointestinal hormone that acts as a secretagogue, stimulating intestinal fluid and electrolyte secretion while simultaneously inhibiting gastric acid production. In VIPoma, the excessive production of VIP leads to profuse, watery diarrhea, often exceeding 3 liters/day, which results in massive fecal potassium loss and subsequent hypokalemia. The inhibition of gastric acid secretion by VIP causes hypochlorhydria or achlorhydria, completing the classic triad of symptoms known as the WDHA (Watery Diarrhea, Hypokalemia, Achlorhydria) syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Necrolytic migratory erythema and hypoaminoacidemia are pathognomonic features of glucagonoma, not VIPoma. While hyperglycemia can occur in VIPoma, it is not the defining feature in combination with these other symptoms.\nOption C (Incorrect): Constipation is the opposite of the severe, watery diarrhea characteristic of VIPoma. While gallstones and hyperglycemia can be associated with some neuroendocrine tumors, they are not part of the classic diagnostic triad for VIPoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is incorrect; VIPoma causes severe hypokalemia due to massive fecal potassium loss. Necrolytic rash is characteristic of glucagonoma, not VIPoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Hormone | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| VIPoma | VIP | Watery diarrhea, hypokalemia, hypochlorhydria |\n| Glucagonoma | Glucagon | Necrolytic migratory erythema, diabetes, weight loss, hypoaminoacidemia |\n| Gastrinoma | Gastrin | Peptic ulcers (Zollinger-Ellison), diarrhea, abdominal pain |\n| Insulinoma | Insulin | Hypoglycemia (Whipple's triad), neuroglycopenic symptoms |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: VIPoma = Watery Diarrhea, Hypokalemia, Achlorhydria (WDHA syndrome).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), VIPomas typically present as pancreatic masses, often solitary and located in the body or tail. Intraoperatively, they are usually well-circumscribed, firm, and may be palpable, sometimes with associated liver metastases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Management of Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors (2020) provide recommendations for diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypokalemia, hypochlorhydria, diarrhea | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hyperglycemia, necrolytic rash, hypoaminoacidemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Constipation, gallstones, hyperglycemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyperkalemia, necrolytic rash, diarrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Patients characteristically present with intermittent severe diarrhea, typically of a watery nature,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
