  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Unroofing simple cysts: definitive relief, cuboidal cells are key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct statements are C and D. Simple hepatic cysts are indeed lined by cuboidal epithelium, and laparoscopic unroofing is a highly effective and standard treatment for symptomatic lesions, offering definitive relief from symptoms like right upper quadrant pain and epigastric fullness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSimple hepatic cysts are the most common benign liver lesions, typically congenital in origin, and do not communicate with the biliary tree. Their characteristic histological feature is a lining of a single layer of cuboidal or columnar epithelium, resembling biliary ductal cells. For symptomatic cysts, especially those over 5 cm, laparoscopic unroofing (deroofing or fenestration) is the preferred surgical approach. This procedure involves excising a portion of the cyst wall, allowing the cyst fluid to drain into the peritoneal cavity, thereby preventing reaccumulation and providing satisfactory, long-term symptom relief with low recurrence rates.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Simple aspiration alone for symptomatic hepatic cysts has a very high recurrence rate (up to 80-100%) because the secretory lining remains intact. It is generally not considered definitive treatment.\nOption B (Incorrect): Simple hepatic cysts typically contain clear, serous fluid, not bile. Bile-stained fluid would suggest communication with the biliary tree, indicating a different pathology such as a choledochal cyst, a complicated simple cyst, or a biliary cystadenoma, which would require a different diagnostic and management approach.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature/Treatment | Simple Hepatic Cyst | Aspiration Alone | Laparoscopic Unroofing |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Congenital, non-communicating | N/A | N/A |\n| Epithelial Lining | Cuboidal/columnar | N/A | N/A |\n| Fluid Content | Clear, serous | Serous (initially) | Serous (drained) |\n| Recurrence Rate | Low (post-unroofing) | High (up to 100%) | Low (5-10%) |\n| Indication | Symptomatic, >5cm | Temporary relief, diagnostic | Symptomatic, large cysts |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic simple liver cysts: unroof them, they're lined by cuboidal cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, as shown in the question's context, simple hepatic cysts appear as anechoic, well-defined lesions with thin walls and posterior acoustic enhancement. Intraoperatively, after unroofing, the smooth, glistening cuboidal lining of the cyst wall is often visible, and clear serous fluid is evacuated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Cystic Liver Lesions (2017). These guidelines recommend surgical intervention, typically laparoscopic unroofing, for symptomatic simple hepatic cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Simple aspiration is indicated for treatment and diagnosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bile stained fluid suggests underlying biliary pathology | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The cyst is likely lined by cuboidal epithelium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laparoscopic unroofing of the cyst can provide satisfactory treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c, d) Answer: c, d** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
