  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't poke if it won't change the outcome!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, as option B correctly identifies a critical principle in the decision-making process for liver mass biopsies. A percutaneous biopsy is primarily indicated when its results are expected to alter the patient's management plan, potentially avoiding more invasive procedures like exploratory laparotomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe decision to perform a biopsy for a hepatic mass hinges on whether the tissue diagnosis will influence treatment. If imaging characteristics are highly suggestive of a resectable malignancy and the patient is a surgical candidate, or if the lesion is clearly benign and requires no intervention, a biopsy may not be necessary. However, if the diagnosis is uncertain and could lead to different treatment pathways (e.g., chemotherapy vs. surgery, or observation vs. intervention), then a biopsy is warranted to guide appropriate management and potentially prevent unnecessary surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fine needle aspiration (FNA) for cytology is not strictly contraindicated for hypervascular masses, although there is an increased risk of bleeding. It is often performed with appropriate precautions.\nOption C (Incorrect): Needle track seeding of tumor is a recognized, albeit rare, complication of percutaneous biopsy, particularly with certain aggressive tumor types like hepatocellular carcinoma or cholangiocarcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Laparoscopy and biopsy play a significant role in the management of liver lesions, especially for staging, obtaining biopsies from difficult locations, assessing resectability, and guiding treatment decisions for indeterminate masses.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Technique | Indication | Risk/Consideration |\n| :--------------- | :--------- | :----------------- |\n| Percutaneous FNA | Cytology, rapid diagnosis | Lower diagnostic yield than core, bleeding, seeding |\n| Percutaneous Core | Histology, immunohistochemistry | Higher diagnostic yield, bleeding, seeding |\n| Laparoscopic Biopsy | Difficult locations, staging, indeterminate lesions | Invasive, general anesthesia, direct visualization |\n| Open Biopsy | When other methods fail, during planned surgery | Most invasive, highest morbidity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biopsy a liver mass only if the result changes management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe image depicts a liver, indicating the anatomical context of the question. On imaging (CT/MRI), hepatic masses can be characterized, but biopsy provides definitive tissue diagnosis. Intraoperatively, a surgeon might perform a wedge or core biopsy under direct visualization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Guidelines for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma 2018: Recommends biopsy for indeterminate lesions or when non-invasive criteria for HCC are not met.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A fine needle aspiration (FNA for cytology is contraindicated for patients  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Percutaneous biopsy should be performed only if results may obviate the nee | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Needle track seeding of tumor is not a risk associated with percutaneous bi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laparoscopy and biopsy play little role in the management of liver lesions | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b) Answer: b** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
