  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 OCP-linked hepatic adenomas: benign by name, dangerous by nature due to hemorrhage.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct options C and D accurately describe key characteristics of hepatic adenomas, which are strongly associated with oral contraceptive use. These lesions, while benign, pose a significant risk of life-threatening hemorrhage and are typically hypervascular on imaging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatic adenomas are benign hepatocellular tumors primarily affecting women, with a strong etiological link to estrogen exposure, particularly from oral contraceptives. Their hypervascular nature, characterized by a rich arterial supply without normal portal venous inflow, makes them prone to spontaneous rupture and life-threatening hemorrhage. This propensity for bleeding, often presenting as acute abdominal pain or shock, necessitates careful management, including surgical resection for symptomatic or large lesions, despite their benign histology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While hepatic adenomas carry a small risk of malignant transformation to hepatocellular carcinoma, they are not considered 'likely premalignant' in the same way as other lesions. The primary concern is hemorrhage.\nOption B (Incorrect): A 99mTc sulfur colloid scan can distinguish hepatic adenoma from focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) by showing a 'cold spot' (adenoma) vs. normal or increased uptake (FNH), but it cannot reliably differentiate an adenoma from a malignant hepatoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatic Adenoma | Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH) | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| OCP Link | Strong | None/Weak | None |\n| Malignant Potential | Small risk of transformation | None | High (is malignant) |\n| Hemorrhage Risk | High | Low | Moderate (can bleed) |\n| 99mTc Sulfur Colloid | Cold spot | Normal/Hot spot | Cold spot |\n| Management | Resection (symptomatic/large) | Observation (most) | Resection/Transplant/Ablation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: OCPs + liver mass = Hepatic Adenoma; always fear hemorrhage.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, hepatic adenomas may show areas of hemorrhage and necrosis. Angiography typically demonstrates a hypervascular tumor with a peripheral blood supply. A 99mTc sulfur colloid scan would show a 'cold spot'. The provided image ![Image](/images/review_bank/37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery_81.jpeg) likely illustrates one of these imaging findings or a gross specimen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance on the Diagnosis and Management of Benign Liver Lesions (2021): Recommends surgical resection for symptomatic hepatic adenomas, those >5 cm, or lesions with suspicious features for malignancy due to hemorrhage risk and malignant transformation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The lesion is likely premalignant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A 99mTc sulfur colloid scan will distinguish this benign lesion from a mali | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The lesion, although benign, may be associated with life-threatening hemorr | ✅ Correct |\n| D | The lesion would be expected to be hypervascular on angiographic study | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D) Hepatic adenomas are clearly linked with the use of oral contraceptives. The likelihood of developin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
