  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FNH: Functional Kupffer cells, conservative care, no OC link.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key characteristics of Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH), a benign liver lesion. It highlights the typical patient demographic and a crucial diagnostic imaging feature, differentiating it from other liver masses like hepatic adenoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNH is unique among liver lesions for retaining functional Kupffer cells, which are specialized macrophages. This physiological characteristic is exploited in technetium-99m sulfur colloid scintigraphy, where FNH appears isodense or 'hot' because the Kupffer cells take up the colloid. This is a critical distinction from hepatic adenomas and most other liver tumors, which lack these functional cells and appear as 'cold' defects. Understanding this cellular composition and its imaging manifestation is fundamental for accurate diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Unlike hepatic adenomas, there is no clear association between FNH and the use of oral contraceptives or other estrogens.\nOption D (Incorrect): FNH is typically asymptomatic, has a low propensity for bleeding or malignant transformation, and is often managed conservatively; excisional biopsy is not indicated in almost all cases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH) | Hepatic Adenoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Demographics | Predominantly young women, also men/children | Young women |\n| OC use | No clear association | Strong association |\n| Malignant potential | Extremely rare | Risk of malignant transformation |\n| Bleeding risk | Low | Higher risk |\n| Kupffer cells | Present | Absent |\n| Radionuclide scan | Isodense/hot | Cold defect |\n| Management | Conservative (if asymptomatic, clear diagnosis) | Resection (due to bleeding/malignancy risk) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FNH has Kupffer cells, adenoma doesn't. Radionuclide scan differentiates.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn technetium-99m sulfur colloid scintigraphy, FNH typically appears isodense or 'hot' due to the presence of functional Kupffer cells, whereas other liver lesions, including hepatic adenomas, appear as 'cold' defects. Intraoperatively, FNH often presents as a well-demarcated, non-encapsulated lesion with a characteristic central stellate scar.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance on the Diagnosis and Management of Benign Liver Lesions (2020) recommends conservative management for asymptomatic FNH with confident diagnosis, and imaging follow-up is generally not required.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The lesion predominantly affects young women | ✅ Correct |\n| B | The lesion is associated with the use of oral contraceptives and other estr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radionucleotide scanning can be useful in the specific diagnosis of FNH | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Excisional biopsy is indicated in almost all cases because of the risk of b | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) Focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) should not be confused with a hepatic adenoma. Although FNH predomin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
