  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When stones are absent, check the squeeze!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that CCK-enhanced cholescintigraphy with assessment of gallbladder ejection fraction (GBEF) is the most specific test for diagnosing gallbladder dyskinesia. This condition presents with classic biliary colic symptoms despite the absence of gallstones on ultrasound.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder dyskinesia, or chronic acalculous cholecystitis, is characterized by impaired gallbladder motility leading to biliary pain. The CCK-enhanced cholescintigraphy (HIDA scan) involves administering a radioactive tracer that is taken up by the liver and excreted into the bile, filling the gallbladder. Cholecystokinin (CCK) is then administered to stimulate gallbladder contraction. The ejection fraction, calculated from the amount of tracer expelled, directly measures gallbladder contractility. A GBEF of less than 35% is considered abnormal and indicative of gallbladder dyskinesia, often leading to symptomatic relief after cholecystectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chronic acalculous cholecystitis or gallbladder dyskinesia is frequently associated with classic biliary colic symptoms, as stated in the provided answer key.\nOption C (Incorrect): An ejection fraction *less than 35%* is considered abnormal and indicative of gallbladder dyskinesia, not greater than 75%.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cholecystectomy *is* indicated for chronic acalculous cholecystitis when symptoms correlate with an abnormal ejection fraction, and it often provides symptom relief.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Symptoms | Diagnostic Test | Abnormal Finding | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Gallbladder Dyskinesia | Biliary colic (no stones) | CCK-HIDA scan | GBEF < 35% | Cholecystectomy |\n| Chronic Acalculous Cholecystitis | Biliary colic (no stones) | CCK-HIDA scan | GBEF < 35% | Cholecystectomy |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis | Ultrasound, HIDA scan | Gallstones, wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, non-visualization of GB on HIDA | Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biliary colic + no stones + low GBEF = gallbladder dyskinesia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe image provided depicts a HIDA scan, which is crucial for diagnosing gallbladder dyskinesia. On a HIDA scan, a low gallbladder ejection fraction (GBEF < 35%) after CCK stimulation is the key finding. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear grossly normal, but its function is impaired.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Surgical Treatment of Gallbladder Dyskinesia (2016) recommend cholecystectomy for patients with biliary-type pain and a low gallbladder ejection fraction on CCK-HIDA scan.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chronic acalculous cholecystitis or gallbladder dyskinesia is seldom associ | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The most specific test for diagnosing gallbladder dyskinesia is CCK-enhance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | An ejection fraction greater than 75% is considered abnormal and indicative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cholecystectomy is not indicated for chronic acalculous cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b) Motility abnormalities of the gallbladder and cystic duct present with symptoms suggesting gallstone** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
