  "answer": "a, b) The primordial anlagen of the liver, extrahepatic bile ducts, gallbladder, and ventral part of the \npancreas develop as a thickened area of entoderm on the ventral surface of the caudal portion of the \nforegut where it joins the midgut. Superior and inferior caudal buds form as the hepatic diverticulum \ngrows out into the ventral mesogastrium. The solid mass of endodermal cells spreading with this \ncephalic bud forms the right and left lobes of the liver. The superior growth of the cranial portion of \nthe hepatic diverticulum, which extends from the duodenum to the liver, results in the formation of \nthe hepatic, common hepatic, and common bile ducts. The caudal portion of the hepatic diverticulum \ndevelops into the gallbladder and cystic duct. The common bile duct is attached to the ventral aspects \nof the duodenum and is in close contact with the ventral pancreatic bud.",
