  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 In gallstone ileus, remove the stone, but don't chase the gallbladder in the frail and old and slow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis debrief accepts the provided answer (A, C, D) as correct. Gallstone ileus is a rare but critical cause of small bowel obstruction, typically affecting elderly patients with a history of gallstone disease, and its diagnosis can often be suggested by plain abdominal radiographs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus arises from a cholecystoenteric fistula, allowing a large gallstone to pass into the intestine and cause mechanical obstruction. This condition is uncommon, accounting for less than 5% of all intestinal obstructions, making option C correct. The typical patient profile, as stated in option D, is indeed elderly individuals with a long history of gallstone disease, who are often frail. Diagnosis can be suggested by plain abdominal radiographs (option A), which may reveal signs such as pneumobilia (intrahepatic biliary air) in the context of small bowel obstruction. The primary surgical management focuses on relieving the obstruction by removing the stone (enterolithotomy), while cholecystectomy is often deferred due to the increased mortality risk in this patient population, making option B incorrect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Primary surgical management for gallstone ileus involves relief of the obstruction via enterolithotomy. Simultaneous cholecystectomy and fistula repair are generally avoided in the acute setting, especially in elderly and ill patients, due to a significantly higher mortality rate (15% vs. 5% for enterolithotomy alone). Cholecystectomy may be considered as a staged procedure if the patient recovers and is a suitable candidate.\nOption A (Correct): Plain abdominal radiographs can suggest the diagnosis by showing signs of small bowel obstruction, pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), and sometimes the ectopic gallstone itself (Rigler's triad).\nOption C (Correct): Gallstone ileus is a rare cause of intestinal obstruction, accounting for less than 5% of all cases.\nOption D (Correct): The condition predominantly affects elderly patients who have a long-standing history of gallstone disease, often leading to chronic inflammation and fistula formation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallstone Ileus | Other SBO Causes (e.g., Adhesions) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | <5% of SBO | Most common cause of SBO (60-70%) |\n| Typical Patient | Elderly, frail, long-standing gallstones | Variable, often post-surgical |\n| Diagnostic Clues | Pneumobilia, ectopic gallstone, SBO on imaging | Dilated bowel loops, transition zone, no pneumobilia |\n| Acute Surgical Goal | Enterolithotomy (stone removal) | Adhesiolysis, resection if strangulated |\n| Cholecystectomy | Often deferred due to high mortality | Not applicable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstone ileus = elderly, rare SBO, pneumobilia, remove stone, defer cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal radiograph, one might see signs of small bowel obstruction (dilated loops, air-fluid levels), pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), and occasionally the obstructing gallstone itself. The provided image `![Image](/images/review_bank/37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery_92.jpeg)` would typically show these radiographic findings, particularly the pneumobilia and dilated bowel loops indicative of obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile specific guidelines for gallstone ileus are less common, the general principles align with the 'American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction' (most recent update typically within the last 5-10 years), which emphasize aggressive fluid resuscitation, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and early surgical intervention for mechanical obstruction, with consideration for patient comorbidities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The diagnosis may be suggested by plain abdominal radiograph | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Primary surgical management consists of relief of obstruction and cholecyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gallstone ileus accounts for less than 5% of all causes of intestinal obstr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Typical patients are elderly with long-standing gallstone disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c, d) Cholecystoenteric fistulas are the most common form of gallbladder perforation accounting for 40% of** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
