  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to biliary, US finds the stones, HIDA finds the acute.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct statements accurately identify ultrasonography as the gold standard for diagnosing cholelithiasis and hepatobiliary scintigraphy (HIDA scan) as the primary confirmatory test for acute cholecystitis, reflecting their high diagnostic accuracy and specific indications in biliary tract disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasonography is the initial imaging modality of choice for suspected cholelithiasis due to its non-invasive nature, lack of radiation, and ability to directly visualize gallstones, sludge, and gallbladder wall changes with high sensitivity and specificity (>95%). Hepatobiliary scintigraphy (HIDA scan) assesses cystic duct patency by tracking tracer uptake and excretion into the biliary tree; non-visualization of the gallbladder after tracer administration confirms cystic duct obstruction, which is the pathophysiologic hallmark of acute cholecystitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Nonvisualization of the gallbladder on oral cholecystogram (OCG) indicates cystic duct obstruction or severe gallbladder dysfunction, but it is not exclusively diagnostic of calculous disease; it could be due to sludge, inflammation, or technical issues. OCG is also largely obsolete.\nOption C (Incorrect): While ultrasound can show signs suggestive of acute or chronic cholecystitis, it is not always the preferred test to definitively distinguish between them, especially when findings are equivocal. HIDA scan is superior for confirming acute cholecystitis by assessing cystic duct patency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Indication | Key Finding | Accuracy/Role |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound (US)** | Cholelithiasis, biliary dilation, initial evaluation of RUQ pain | Gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, CBD dilation | High sensitivity/specificity for stones (>95%); first-line imaging |\n| **Hepatobiliary Scintigraphy (HIDA)** | Acute cholecystitis | Non-visualization of gallbladder | High sensitivity/specificity for acute cholecystitis (90-97%); confirms cystic duct obstruction |\n| **CT Scan** | Complications of biliary disease (perforation, abscess), pancreatitis, malignancy, alternative diagnoses | Pericholecystic inflammation, fluid collections, mass lesions, calcifications | Good for complications and alternative diagnoses; less sensitive for stones than US |\n| **MRCP (Magnetic Resonance Cholangiopancreatography)** | Choledocholithiasis, biliary strictures, pancreaticobiliary anatomy | Stones in bile ducts, strictures, anomalous anatomy | Non-invasive alternative to ERCP for diagnosis of ductal pathology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: US for stones, HIDA for acute cholecystitis – know their primary roles.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as echogenic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing. In acute cholecystitis, ultrasound may show gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a sonographic Murphy's sign. A HIDA scan showing no tracer uptake in the gallbladder after 60-90 minutes (or 4 hours) confirms cystic duct obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. They recommend ultrasound as the initial imaging modality and HIDA scan for confirmation when ultrasound is equivocal.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Nonvisualization of the gallbladder on oral cholecystogram is diagnostic of | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ultrasonography has a diagnostic accuracy and sensitivity for cholelithiasi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ultrasonography is the preferred test to distinguish chronic from acute cho | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatobiliary scintigraphy is primarily indicated to confirm the clinical d | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, d) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
