  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just remove the gallbladder; clear the duct!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Options A, B, and D represent the primary and widely accepted strategies for managing common bile duct stones identified during laparoscopic cholecystectomy, offering a spectrum of approaches from single-stage laparoscopic to staged endoscopic or open conversion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraoperative identification of CBD stones necessitates a plan for removal. Transcystic duct exploration (B) is a minimally invasive, single-stage laparoscopic approach, often preferred for smaller stones. Postoperative ERCP (D) is a common staged approach, allowing completion of cholecystectomy and subsequent endoscopic stone removal, especially if laparoscopic expertise is limited or stones are numerous. Conversion to open cholecystectomy with common duct exploration (A) remains a safe and effective option, particularly for large or impacted stones, or when laparoscopic techniques fail.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Laparoscopic choledochotomy, while technically possible, is generally reserved for larger or impacted stones not amenable to transcystic exploration. It is more invasive than transcystic exploration and carries a higher risk of bile leak and stricture compared to transcystic or postoperative ERCP, making it less of a primary \"appropriate option\" for *common* stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Approach | Invasiveness | Timing | Indications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transcystic Exploration | Minimally Invasive | Single-stage | Small, few stones, favorable anatomy |\n| Laparoscopic Choledochotomy | Minimally Invasive | Single-stage | Larger/impacted stones, failed transcystic |\n| Postoperative ERCP | Minimally Invasive (Endoscopic) | Staged | Small/medium stones, surgeon preference, failed laparoscopic |\n| Open CBD Exploration | Invasive | Single-stage | Large/impacted stones, failed laparoscopic/endoscopic, complex anatomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intraoperative CBD stones: transcystic first, ERCP second, open as a last resort.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperative cholangiogram (IOC) is crucial for confirming CBD stones, their number, size, and location, guiding the choice of management strategy. Stones appear as filling defects within the common bile duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Bile Duct Stones (2017) recommends a tailored approach based on patient factors, stone characteristics, and surgeon expertise, including transcystic exploration, laparoscopic choledochotomy, or postoperative ERCP.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Conversion to open cholecystectomy and common duct exploration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Transcystic duct dilatation and exploration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Laparoscopic choledochotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Complete the laparoscopic cholecystectomy with postoperative ERCP and stone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, d) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
