  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just remove the stone, check the wall; incidental cancer can be a silent call!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A, B, and D are correct. This question highlights the critical management decisions and prognostic implications for incidentally discovered gallbladder carcinoma, emphasizing that early-stage disease can be cured by cholecystectomy alone, while deeper invasion necessitates more aggressive re-resection due to high rates of residual disease and worse prognosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder carcinoma limited to the mucosa and/or submucosa (T1a/T1b) has an excellent prognosis with cholecystectomy alone, often approaching 100% 5-year survival, as lymphatic invasion is rare at these superficial stages (Option A). However, if the carcinoma involves deeper layers of the gallbladder wall (T2 or greater), the prognosis significantly worsens due to increased risk of lymphatic and vascular spread (Option B). For such deeper invasions, an \"extended cholecystectomy\" (resection of liver segments IVb/V and regional lymphadenectomy) is indicated to clear potential microscopic residual disease in the liver bed and regional lymph nodes, which are common pathways for spread (Option D).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): The provided text explicitly states that reexploration for incidentally discovered gallbladder cancer will \"likely show evidence of residual disease in the lymph nodes or adjacent liver.\" Therefore, the chance of finding residual disease is high, not low.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage | Depth of Invasion | Treatment | 5-Year Survival (approx.) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| T1a | Lamina propria | Cholecystectomy alone | ~100% |\n| T1b | Muscularis propria | Cholecystectomy alone | ~64% |\n| T2+ | Beyond muscularis propria | Extended Cholecystectomy | Significantly worse (variable) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Incidental GB cancer: T1a/T1b cholecystectomy; T2+ extended cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe image provided is a placeholder and does not offer diagnostic information. Intraoperatively, suspicious findings like a thickened gallbladder wall, mass, or adhesions to the liver bed should prompt frozen section biopsy. All cholecystectomy specimens must be opened and inspected for suspicious lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (e.g., Version 2.2023) recommend re-resection with extended cholecystectomy for T1b and higher stages of incidentally discovered gallbladder carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | If the gallbladder carcinoma is limited to the mucosa and/or submucosa, cho | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | If the carcinoma involves deeper layers of the gallbladder wall, the progno | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | If reoperation is performed, the chance of finding residual disease will be | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | If a full thickness tumor had been recognized at the time of cholecystectom | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, d) Gallbladder cancers with the best prognosis are those that are found incidentally at the time of cho** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
