  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fixed polyp, fixed problem: when in doubt, take it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key characteristics of gallbladder polyps. Sonographically, they appear as fixed filling defects, and benign polyps can indeed cause symptoms indistinguishable from gallstones, necessitating careful evaluation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder polyps are intraluminal lesions that do not move with changes in patient position, a critical distinguishing feature from gallstones which are mobile. Benign polyps, particularly cholesterol polyps, can cause biliary-type symptoms such as right upper quadrant pain, nausea, and fatty food intolerance, mimicking cholelithiasis. This symptomatic overlap underscores the challenge in clinical differentiation and the importance of imaging characteristics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Ultrasonography cannot reliably distinguish benign from malignant gallbladder lesions. While certain features like size, growth, and vascularity can raise suspicion, definitive diagnosis often requires histopathology.\nOption D (Incorrect): An asymptomatic gallbladder polyp 1 cm in size typically warrants cholecystectomy due to the increased risk of malignancy at this size, rather than serial ultrasounds. Current guidelines generally recommend intervention for polyps ≥ 1 cm.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallbladder Polyp | Gallstone (Cholelithiasis) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mobility on US** | Fixed filling defect | Mobile echogenic focus |\n| **Posterior Shadowing** | Absent | Present |\n| **Symptoms** | RUQ pain, nausea, fatty food intolerance (can be asymptomatic) | RUQ pain, biliary colic, nausea, fatty food intolerance |\n| **Malignancy Risk** | Increases with size (≥ 1 cm), age, primary sclerosing cholangitis | None (but can cause complications) |\n| **Management (≥ 1 cm)** | Cholecystectomy | Cholecystectomy (if symptomatic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fixed polyp ≥ 1 cm or symptomatic = cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a gallbladder polyp appears as an echogenic lesion protruding into the lumen that does not move with changes in patient position and typically does not cast an acoustic shadow. This differentiates it from a gallstone, which is mobile and produces shadowing. CT or MRI may further characterize the lesion, but definitive benign vs. malignant distinction is often not possible preoperatively.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Clinical Practice Update on the Diagnosis and Management of Gallbladder Polyps: 2020.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sonographic findings of a gallbladder polyp include a filling defect which  | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Benign gallbladder polyps can cause symptoms similar to those caused by gal | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Ultrasonography can readily distinguish benign from malignant gallbladder l | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | An asymptomatic gallbladder polyp 1 cm in size can usually be followed with | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B) Benign gallbladder polyps cause symptoms similar to those caused by cholelithiasis. Biliary symptoms** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
