  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PSC: Medical's a bust, surgery for focal, transplant for the rest!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options highlight that specific surgical interventions like biliary reconstruction for focal strictures can be effective in selected PSC patients, and that liver transplantation offers comparable survival rates to other indications. This reflects the current understanding of PSC management, which often relies on surgical or transplant interventions due to limited medical options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary sclerosing cholangitis often presents with diffuse strictures, but a subset of patients develops dominant, focal strictures, particularly at the hepatic duct bifurcation. For these selected patients without established cirrhosis, resection of the bifurcation and long-term transhepatic stenting can yield excellent results by restoring biliary flow. When the disease is advanced with established cirrhosis, or when surgical reconstruction is not feasible, hepatic transplantation becomes the definitive treatment, offering survival rates comparable to those for other end-stage liver diseases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): There is no known specific, effective medical therapy for PSC that halts disease progression or improves survival, although some agents like ursodeoxycholic acid may improve LFTs and symptoms.\nOption C (Incorrect): Biliary reconstruction is not reserved only for patients with established biliary cirrhosis. In fact, results are excellent in patients without established cirrhosis, while those with cirrhosis have high morbidity/mortality and poor long-term results from reconstruction, making transplantation a better option for them.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication | Outcome/Consideration |\n| :----------------- | :--------- | :-------------------- |\n| Medical Therapy (e.g., UDCA) | Symptomatic relief, LFT improvement | No specific effective therapy to halt progression or improve survival |\n| Biliary Reconstruction (Resection + Stenting) | Focal strictures (e.g., hepatic duct bifurcation) | Excellent results if no established cirrhosis; poor if cirrhosis present |\n| Hepatic Transplantation | Established biliary cirrhosis, end-stage liver disease, recurrent cholangitis | Definitive treatment; survival rates similar to other transplant indications |\n| Endoscopic/Radiologic Dilation | Dominant strictures | Temporary relief, often used as bridge or palliative |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSC management: medical for symptoms, surgery for focal strictures, transplant for cirrhosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCholangiography (ERCP/MRCP) in PSC typically shows multifocal stricturing and dilations, giving a 'beaded' appearance. Intraoperatively, the bile ducts may appear thickened and inflamed, with a dominant stricture at the hepatic duct bifurcation requiring careful dissection and reconstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance on the Diagnosis and Management of Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (2023). It recommends UDCA for symptoms but notes no survival benefit, and discusses surgical/transplant options.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A number of immunosuppressive oral agents can provide specific effective tr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biliary reconstruction with long-term transanastomotic stents can be useful | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Biliary reconstruction should be reserved only for patients with establishe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatic transplantation for primary sclerosing cholangitis can be associate | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) There is no known specific, effective medical therapy for primary sclerosing cholangitis. Although e** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 37358425-Liver-Mcq-Surgery.pdf**\n",
